Note:
==============================================================================
KEY_DERIVATION - High-level KDF wrappers (HKDF, Argon2id, PBKDF2, scrypt)
==============================================================================

This module is the unified front for key-derivation operations. It provides:

  - hkdf_extract_then_expand : RFC 5869 HKDF (parametric on the underlying
                               hash algorithm); delegates to hkdf.runa.

  - argon2id_derive          : RFC 9106 Argon2id; delegates to argon2id.runa.

  - pbkdf2_hmac              : RFC 8018 PBKDF2 with HMAC-SHA-256 or SHA-512;
                               implemented in-tree on top of hmac.runa.

  - scrypt                   : RFC 7914 scrypt; implemented in-tree on top of
                               sha2.runa (via PBKDF2-SHA256) and a fresh
                               Salsa20 core, BlockMix, ROMix sequence.

  - KDF_derive               : Tag-driven dispatcher accepting the algorithm
                               ID from crypto_algorithm.runa.

References:
- RFC 5869: HKDF.
- RFC 9106: Argon2id.
- RFC 8018: PBKDF2.
- RFC 7914: scrypt.
- FIPS 180-4 / RFC 6234: SHA-2.
- HC#11 TASC: crypto-agility mandate.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/crypto_identity/crypto_algorithm.runa" as Alg
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/secure_memory.runa" as Secure
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/hkdf.runa" as Hkdf
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/argon2id.runa" as Argon2id
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/hmac.runa" as Hmac
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/sha2.runa" as Sha2

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1: hkdf_extract_then_expand - parametric HKDF
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
RFC 5869 HKDF in the standard extract-then-expand composition. The salt
and info parameters are non-secret per RFC 5869 section 3. ikm is the
input keying material; output length is the desired derived key size in
bytes.

The hash parameter selects the underlying HMAC hash:
  - ALG_SHA2_256 (300) -> HKDF-SHA-256, max output = 255 * 32 = 8160 bytes
  - ALG_SHA2_384 (301) -> HKDF-SHA-384, max output = 255 * 48 = 12240 bytes
  - ALG_SHA2_512 (302) -> HKDF-SHA-512, max output = 255 * 64 = 16320 bytes

Other hash IDs return 0.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Dispatch on hash_algorithm tag to the corresponding hkdf_shaXXX call
that performs the extract-then-expand sequence in one shot.

The output buffer must be pre-allocated by the caller with at least
output_length bytes.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(output_length / hash_block + 1) HMAC calls for extract; O(ceil(output_length /
hash_size)) HMAC calls for expand. Total: bounded by ceil(L/HashLen) + 1
HMACs.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The PRK (intermediate pseudorandom key) is stored inside an arena
allocation by hkdf.runa and is cleared by arena_destroy.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hkdf_extract_then_expand" takes arena as Integer, salt as Integer, salt_length as Integer, ikm as Integer, ikm_length as Integer, info as Integer, info_length as Integer, output_length as Integer, hash_algorithm as Integer, out_okm as Integer returns Integer:
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ikm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If out_okm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output_length is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If hash_algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SHA2_256:
        If output_length is greater than 8160:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return Hkdf.hkdf_sha256(arena, salt, salt_length, ikm, ikm_length, info, info_length, output_length, out_okm)
    End If
    If hash_algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SHA2_384:
        If output_length is greater than 12240:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return Hkdf.hkdf_sha384(arena, salt, salt_length, ikm, ikm_length, info, info_length, output_length, out_okm)
    End If
    If hash_algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SHA2_512:
        If output_length is greater than 16320:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return Hkdf.hkdf_sha512(arena, salt, salt_length, ikm, ikm_length, info, info_length, output_length, out_okm)
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2: argon2id_derive - RFC 9106 Argon2id
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Argon2id key derivation per RFC 9106. The id-variant is the recommended
default because it combines Argon2i's side-channel resistance for the
first half-pass with Argon2d's GPU-attack resistance for the remainder.

Parameter recommendations from RFC 9106 section 4:
  - time_cost: 2 or 3
  - memory_kib: 65536 (64 MiB) for interactive logins, 1048576 (1 GiB)
                for backups/cold storage
  - parallelism: matches available cores

The output length must be at least 4 bytes per RFC 9106 section 3.1.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to argon2id.runa's argon2id_hash which implements the full
Argon2id algorithm. We pass empty secret and associated_data fields
(both optional per RFC 9106 section 3.1).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(memory_kib * time_cost). For 64 MiB and t=3 this is dominated by
~200 million Blake2b compressions; expect ~1 second on modern hardware.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The password input is treated as secret. The internal memory blocks
are inside the arena; if the caller wants no-trace storage, use a
dedicated short-lived arena.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "argon2id_derive" takes arena as Integer, password as Integer, password_len as Integer, salt as Integer, salt_len as Integer, time_cost as Integer, memory_kib as Integer, parallelism as Integer, output_len as Integer, output as Integer returns Integer:
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If password is equal to 0:
        If password_len is not equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    If salt is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If salt_len is less than 8:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output_len is less than 4:
        Return 0
    End If
    If time_cost is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If parallelism is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return Argon2id.argon2id_hash(password, password_len, salt, salt_len, 0, 0, 0, 0, memory_kib, time_cost, parallelism, output, output_len)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3: pbkdf2_hmac - RFC 8018 PBKDF2 with HMAC
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
PBKDF2 per RFC 8018 section 5.2 with HMAC as the PRF. Generates a
derived key of `output_len` bytes by iterating HMAC over a counter-
stamped salt for `iterations` rounds, then concatenating the per-block
outputs.

Block i of the output is:
  T_i = F(P, S, c, i)
  F(P, S, c, i) = U_1 XOR U_2 XOR ... XOR U_c
  U_1 = HMAC(P, S || INT(i))
  U_j = HMAC(P, U_{j-1})        for j = 2..c

INT(i) is i encoded as a 4-byte big-endian integer.

Supported hashes:
  - ALG_SHA2_256: HMAC-SHA-256 (default; hLen = 32)
  - ALG_SHA2_512: HMAC-SHA-512 (hLen = 64)

Iterations should be at least 600000 for SHA-256 per OWASP 2023 guidance,
or 210000 for SHA-512.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Steps:
  1. Compute hLen for the selected hash.
  2. Compute the number of blocks needed: ceil(output_len / hLen).
  3. For each block i from 1 to num_blocks:
     a. Build salt || INT(i) in scratch.
     b. U_1 = HMAC(P, salt||INT(i)).
     c. For j = 2..iterations:
        U_j = HMAC(P, U_{j-1}).
     d. T_i = XOR of all U_j.
  4. Concatenate T_1 || T_2 || ... and write first output_len bytes.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(iterations * num_blocks) HMAC calls. With iterations=600000 and 32-byte
output (single block), that's 600000 HMAC-SHA-256 calls (~200-500 ms).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The password is fed into HMAC's key slot. The intermediate U_j values
are in arena scratch and reclaimed by arena_destroy.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pbkdf2_hmac" takes arena as Integer, password as Integer, password_len as Integer, salt as Integer, salt_len as Integer, iterations as Integer, output_len as Integer, hash_algorithm as Integer, output as Integer returns Integer:
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If password is equal to 0:
        If password_len is not equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    If salt is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output_len is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If iterations is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let h_len be 0
    If hash_algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SHA2_256:
        Set h_len to 32
    End If
    If hash_algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SHA2_512:
        Set h_len to 64
    End If
    If h_len is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Maximum output: (2^32 - 1) * h_len. Practical guard: 1 MiB.
    If output_len is greater than 1048576:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let num_blocks be output_len plus h_len
    Set num_blocks to num_blocks minus 1
    Set num_blocks to num_blocks divided by h_len

    Let salted be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, salt_len plus 4)
    If salted is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_copy(salted, salt, salt_len)

    Let u_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, h_len)
    If u_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let t_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, h_len)
    If t_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let block_idx be 1
    Let out_off be 0
    While block_idx is less than (num_blocks plus 1):
        Note: Encode INT(block_idx) at the end of salted.
        Memory.memory_set_byte(salted, salt_len, (block_idx divided by 16777216) modulo by 256)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(salted, salt_len plus 1, (block_idx divided by 65536) modulo by 256)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(salted, salt_len plus 2, (block_idx divided by 256) modulo by 256)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(salted, salt_len plus 3, block_idx modulo by 256)

        Note: U_1 = HMAC(P, salt||INT(i)).
        Let rc_u1 be 0
        If hash_algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SHA2_256:
            Set rc_u1 to Hmac.hmac_sha256(arena, password, password_len, salted, salt_len plus 4, u_buf)
        End If
        If hash_algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SHA2_512:
            Set rc_u1 to Hmac.hmac_sha512(arena, password, password_len, salted, salt_len plus 4, u_buf)
        End If
        If rc_u1 is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: T_i = U_1 initially.
        Memory.memory_copy(t_buf, u_buf, h_len)

        Note: Iterate U_j = HMAC(P, U_{j-1}) and XOR into T_i.
        Let j_idx be 2
        While j_idx is less than (iterations plus 1):
            Let scratch be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, h_len)
            If scratch is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Let rc_uj be 0
            If hash_algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SHA2_256:
                Set rc_uj to Hmac.hmac_sha256(arena, password, password_len, u_buf, h_len, scratch)
            End If
            If hash_algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SHA2_512:
                Set rc_uj to Hmac.hmac_sha512(arena, password, password_len, u_buf, h_len, scratch)
            End If
            If rc_uj is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Memory.memory_copy(u_buf, scratch, h_len)
            Let xi be 0
            While xi is less than h_len:
                Let t_val be Memory.memory_get_byte(t_buf, xi)
                Let u_val be Memory.memory_get_byte(u_buf, xi)
                Note: bitwise XOR via Memory.memory_get_byte op; use arithmetic XOR with bit-set/clear.
                Memory.memory_set_byte(t_buf, xi, pbkdf2_byte_xor(t_val, u_val))
                Set xi to xi plus 1
            End While
            Set j_idx to j_idx plus 1
        End While

        Note: Copy T_i into the output, capping at output_len.
        Let copy_len be h_len
        Let remaining be output_len minus out_off
        If remaining is less than copy_len:
            Set copy_len to remaining
        End If
        Memory.memory_copy(output plus out_off, t_buf, copy_len)
        Set out_off to out_off plus copy_len

        Set block_idx to block_idx plus 1
    End While

    Secure.secure_zero(u_buf, h_len)
    Secure.secure_zero(t_buf, h_len)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4: pbkdf2_byte_xor - byte-XOR helper
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Computes a XOR b for byte-sized operands using bit-by-bit composition.
Returns the XOR result as an integer in 0..255.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
For each bit position 0..7, set the result bit to (a_bit XOR b_bit) =
((a_bit OR b_bit) AND NOT (a_bit AND b_bit)) computed arithmetically.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(8). 8 iterations of bit extraction.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
No secret-dependent branching.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pbkdf2_byte_xor" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be 0
    Let bit_idx be 0
    Let weight be 1
    While bit_idx is less than 8:
        Let a_bit be (a divided by weight) modulo by 2
        Let b_bit be (b divided by weight) modulo by 2
        Let x_bit be 0
        If a_bit is not equal to b_bit:
            Set x_bit to 1
        End If
        Set result to result plus (x_bit multiplied by weight)
        Set weight to weight multiplied by 2
        Set bit_idx to bit_idx plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5: scrypt - RFC 7914
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Scrypt KDF per RFC 7914. Designed to be sequential-memory-hard, making
hardware attacks (ASIC/FPGA) expensive.

Parameters:
  - N: CPU/memory cost; power of 2, e.g. 16384, 32768, 1048576.
  - r: block size factor; typical 8.
  - p: parallelization; typical 1.
  - output_len: derived key length in bytes.

The algorithm:
  1. B = PBKDF2-SHA256(password, salt, 1, p*128*r)  -- expand to p blocks.
  2. For i in 0..p-1: B_i = scryptROMix(r, B_i, N).
  3. DK = PBKDF2-SHA256(password, B, 1, dkLen).

scryptROMix:
  X = B
  for i in 0..N-1: V[i] = X; X = scryptBlockMix(X)
  for i in 0..N-1: j = Integerify(X) mod N; X = scryptBlockMix(X XOR V[j])
  return X

scryptBlockMix:
  X = B[2r-1]   (last 64-byte chunk)
  for i in 0..2r-1: X = Salsa(X XOR B[i]); Y[i] = X
  return Y[0], Y[2], ..., Y[2r-2], Y[1], Y[3], ..., Y[2r-1]
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Implemented in full as a sequence of:
  - PBKDF2-SHA256 setup expansion (using pbkdf2_hmac above).
  - For each of p blocks: scryptROMix on a 128*r byte block.
  - PBKDF2-SHA256 final compression to dkLen bytes.

The Salsa20/8 core is implemented inline as scrypt_salsa20_8.
BlockMix uses the Salsa20/8 core as its inner permutation.

Memory cost: p * N * 128 * r bytes for V. Caller is responsible for
ensuring the arena can hold this; standard parameters (N=16384, r=8,
p=1) need 128 * 16384 * 8 = 16 MiB.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(N * r * 2 * p) Salsa20/8 calls. For (N=16384, r=8, p=1): ~262144
Salsa20/8 calls; ~100-500 ms on modern hardware.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The password is consumed in PBKDF2's HMAC key slot. The V array holds
intermediate state derived from the password and is wiped on arena
destruction.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt" takes arena as Integer, password as Integer, password_len as Integer, salt as Integer, salt_len as Integer, n_cost as Integer, r as Integer, p as Integer, output_len as Integer, output as Integer returns Integer:
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If password is equal to 0:
        If password_len is not equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    If salt is equal to 0:
        If salt_len is not equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    If output is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output_len is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If n_cost is less than 2:
        Return 0
    End If
    If r is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If p is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: N must be a power of 2. Check: n_cost & (n_cost-1) == 0.
    Let n_check be scrypt_is_power_of_two(n_cost)
    If n_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let block_bytes be 128 multiplied by r

    Note: Phase 1: B = PBKDF2-SHA256(P, S, 1, p*block_bytes).
    Let total_b_bytes be p multiplied by block_bytes
    Let b_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, total_b_bytes)
    If b_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc1 be pbkdf2_hmac(arena, password, password_len, salt, salt_len, 1, total_b_bytes, Alg.ALG_SHA2_256, b_buf)
    If rc1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Phase 2: ROMix each B_i in place.
    Let pi be 0
    While pi is less than p:
        Let b_i be b_buf plus (pi multiplied by block_bytes)
        Let rmix be scrypt_romix(arena, b_i, r, n_cost)
        If rmix is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set pi to pi plus 1
    End While

    Note: Phase 3: DK = PBKDF2-SHA256(P, B, 1, output_len).
    Return pbkdf2_hmac(arena, password, password_len, b_buf, total_b_bytes, 1, output_len, Alg.ALG_SHA2_256, output)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6: scrypt_is_power_of_two helper
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Check whether n_cost is a power of 2 by repeated halving.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Halve n_cost while it's even and greater than 1; if final value is 1,
it was a power of 2.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(log2 n_cost).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
n_cost is a public parameter.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_is_power_of_two" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is less than 2:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let v be n
    While v is greater than 1:
        If v modulo by 2 is not equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set v to v divided by 2
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7: scrypt_romix - the memory-hard mixing function
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Apply scryptROMix to a single 128*r byte block in place.

Steps:
  X = B (input block, 128*r bytes)
  for i in 0..N-1: V[i] = X; X = scryptBlockMix(X)
  for i in 0..N-1: j = Integerify(X) mod N; X = scryptBlockMix(X XOR V[j])
  B = X

Integerify reads the last 64 bytes of X as a little-endian integer and
takes it mod N.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates the V array (N * 128 * r bytes) and a scratch buffer for X.
Runs the two N-step loops as specified.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(N * r) Salsa20/8 calls plus O(N * r) memcpy.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The V array contains password-derived state; reclaimed by arena_destroy.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_romix" takes arena as Integer, b_in_out as Integer, r as Integer, n_cost as Integer returns Integer:
    Let block_bytes be 128 multiplied by r
    Let v_array be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, n_cost multiplied by block_bytes)
    If v_array is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let x_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, block_bytes)
    If x_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_copy(x_buf, b_in_out, block_bytes)

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n_cost:
        Memory.memory_copy(v_array plus (i multiplied by block_bytes), x_buf, block_bytes)
        Let bm be scrypt_block_mix(arena, x_buf, r)
        If bm is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set i to 0
    While i is less than n_cost:
        Note: Integerify: read last 64 bytes of X, take first 8 LE bytes as int,
        Note: mod N. We use bytes [block_bytes-64..block_bytes-57] as the
        Note: 64-bit little-endian integer.
        Let j_idx be scrypt_integerify(x_buf, block_bytes, n_cost)
        Let v_block be v_array plus (j_idx multiplied by block_bytes)
        Note: X = X XOR V[j].
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than block_bytes:
            Let xv be Memory.memory_get_byte(x_buf, k)
            Let vv be Memory.memory_get_byte(v_block, k)
            Memory.memory_set_byte(x_buf, k, pbkdf2_byte_xor(xv, vv))
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
        Let bm2 be scrypt_block_mix(arena, x_buf, r)
        If bm2 is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Memory.memory_copy(b_in_out, x_buf, block_bytes)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 8: scrypt_integerify
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Integerify(X) per RFC 7914 section 5: reads the last 64 bytes of X
(the final Salsa block) and takes the first 4 bytes as a 32-bit
little-endian integer modulo N.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read bytes at offset (block_bytes - 64) through (block_bytes - 61) as a
little-endian 32-bit number, then mod n_cost. For N up to 2^31 this is
sufficient.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). Four byte loads.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The result is a public index; secret-dependent but the access pattern
through V is one of the fundamental scrypt security properties (memory
hardness).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_integerify" takes x_buf as Integer, block_bytes as Integer, n_cost as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base_off be block_bytes minus 64
    Let b0 be Memory.memory_get_byte(x_buf, base_off)
    Let b1 be Memory.memory_get_byte(x_buf, base_off plus 1)
    Let b2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(x_buf, base_off plus 2)
    Let b3 be Memory.memory_get_byte(x_buf, base_off plus 3)
    Let v32 be b0 plus (b1 multiplied by 256) plus (b2 multiplied by 65536) plus (b3 multiplied by 16777216)
    Return v32 modulo by n_cost
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 9: scrypt_block_mix
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
BlockMix per RFC 7914 section 6:
  X = B[2r-1]
  for i in 0..2r-1: X = Salsa(X XOR B[i]); Y[i] = X
  return Y[0], Y[2], ..., Y[2r-2], Y[1], Y[3], ..., Y[2r-1]

Operates on a 128*r byte buffer in place by allocating scratch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Uses two 64-byte scratch buffers: x_state and tmp. The Y array reorders
to put even-indexed Y_i before odd-indexed Y_i.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(r) Salsa20/8 invocations.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal state; reclaimed by arena_destroy.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_block_mix" takes arena as Integer, b_inout as Integer, r as Integer returns Integer:
    Let block_bytes be 128 multiplied by r
    Let x_state be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 64)
    If x_state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let y_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, block_bytes)
    If y_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Copy the last 64-byte block of B into X.
    Memory.memory_copy(x_state, b_inout plus (block_bytes minus 64), 64)

    Let i be 0
    Let two_r be 2 multiplied by r
    While i is less than two_r:
        Note: X = Salsa(X XOR B[i]).
        Let bi_ptr be b_inout plus (i multiplied by 64)
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than 64:
            Let xv be Memory.memory_get_byte(x_state, k)
            Let bv be Memory.memory_get_byte(bi_ptr, k)
            Memory.memory_set_byte(x_state, k, pbkdf2_byte_xor(xv, bv))
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
        Let sa be scrypt_salsa20_8(x_state)
        If sa is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Memory.memory_copy(y_buf plus (i multiplied by 64), x_state, 64)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Reorder Y into B: even-indexed first (Y_0,Y_2,...), then odd-indexed.
    Let out_off be 0
    Let even_idx be 0
    While even_idx is less than two_r:
        Memory.memory_copy(b_inout plus out_off, y_buf plus (even_idx multiplied by 64), 64)
        Set out_off to out_off plus 64
        Set even_idx to even_idx plus 2
    End While
    Let odd_idx be 1
    While odd_idx is less than two_r:
        Memory.memory_copy(b_inout plus out_off, y_buf plus (odd_idx multiplied by 64), 64)
        Set out_off to out_off plus 64
        Set odd_idx to odd_idx plus 2
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 10: scrypt_salsa20_8 - Salsa20/8 core
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Salsa20/8 core per RFC 7914 section 3 (which references RFC 8439's
Salsa20). Operates on a 64-byte input as 16 little-endian 32-bit words.

The core is a 4-round (8 half-rounds total) double-round Salsa20 with
the final addition: x = x + Salsa20/8(x) where Salsa20/8 is 4 double
rounds of column/row mixing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Steps:
  1. Load 16 LE32 words from the input buffer into a local array x[].
  2. Save initial state as orig[].
  3. For 4 double-rounds (8 half-rounds), apply the column round then
     the row round.
  4. Add x[i] = (x[i] + orig[i]) mod 2^32.
  5. Write back as LE32.

Column round:
  R(x[ 4]^=R(x[ 0]+x[12], 7))
  R(x[ 8]^=R(x[ 4]+x[ 0], 9))
  R(x[12]^=R(x[ 8]+x[ 4],13))
  R(x[ 0]^=R(x[12]+x[ 8],18))
  ... (4 column sets)
Row round: same shape with rotated indices.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(64). 8 half-rounds * 16 operations each = 128 ARX operations.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The Salsa20/8 core is the cryptographic primitive at the heart of
scrypt's memory hardness; correctness is essential.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_salsa20_8" takes block_64 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Load 16 LE32 words into the local "registers" using positions 0..15.
    Note: We allocate a small 16*8=128 byte work buffer on the stack via local lets
    Note: with consistent naming. Because Runa doesn't have arrays here we keep
    Note: them as 16 named lets.
    Let w0 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 0)
    Let w1 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 4)
    Let w2 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 8)
    Let w3 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 12)
    Let w4 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 16)
    Let w5 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 20)
    Let w6 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 24)
    Let w7 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 28)
    Let w8 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 32)
    Let w9 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 36)
    Let w10 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 40)
    Let w11 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 44)
    Let w12 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 48)
    Let w13 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 52)
    Let w14 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 56)
    Let w15 be scrypt_load_le32(block_64, 60)

    Let o0 be w0
    Let o1 be w1
    Let o2 be w2
    Let o3 be w3
    Let o4 be w4
    Let o5 be w5
    Let o6 be w6
    Let o7 be w7
    Let o8 be w8
    Let o9 be w9
    Let o10 be w10
    Let o11 be w11
    Let o12 be w12
    Let o13 be w13
    Let o14 be w14
    Let o15 be w15

    Let round_idx be 0
    While round_idx is less than 4:
        Note: Column round.
        Set w4 to scrypt_xor32(w4, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w0, w12), 7))
        Set w8 to scrypt_xor32(w8, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w4, w0), 9))
        Set w12 to scrypt_xor32(w12, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w8, w4), 13))
        Set w0 to scrypt_xor32(w0, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w12, w8), 18))

        Set w9 to scrypt_xor32(w9, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w5, w1), 7))
        Set w13 to scrypt_xor32(w13, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w9, w5), 9))
        Set w1 to scrypt_xor32(w1, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w13, w9), 13))
        Set w5 to scrypt_xor32(w5, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w1, w13), 18))

        Set w14 to scrypt_xor32(w14, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w10, w6), 7))
        Set w2 to scrypt_xor32(w2, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w14, w10), 9))
        Set w6 to scrypt_xor32(w6, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w2, w14), 13))
        Set w10 to scrypt_xor32(w10, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w6, w2), 18))

        Set w3 to scrypt_xor32(w3, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w15, w11), 7))
        Set w7 to scrypt_xor32(w7, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w3, w15), 9))
        Set w11 to scrypt_xor32(w11, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w7, w3), 13))
        Set w15 to scrypt_xor32(w15, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w11, w7), 18))

        Note: Row round.
        Set w1 to scrypt_xor32(w1, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w0, w3), 7))
        Set w2 to scrypt_xor32(w2, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w1, w0), 9))
        Set w3 to scrypt_xor32(w3, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w2, w1), 13))
        Set w0 to scrypt_xor32(w0, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w3, w2), 18))

        Set w6 to scrypt_xor32(w6, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w5, w4), 7))
        Set w7 to scrypt_xor32(w7, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w6, w5), 9))
        Set w4 to scrypt_xor32(w4, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w7, w6), 13))
        Set w5 to scrypt_xor32(w5, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w4, w7), 18))

        Set w11 to scrypt_xor32(w11, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w10, w9), 7))
        Set w8 to scrypt_xor32(w8, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w11, w10), 9))
        Set w9 to scrypt_xor32(w9, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w8, w11), 13))
        Set w10 to scrypt_xor32(w10, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w9, w8), 18))

        Set w12 to scrypt_xor32(w12, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w15, w14), 7))
        Set w13 to scrypt_xor32(w13, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w12, w15), 9))
        Set w14 to scrypt_xor32(w14, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w13, w12), 13))
        Set w15 to scrypt_xor32(w15, scrypt_rotl32(scrypt_add32(w14, w13), 18))

        Set round_idx to round_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Final add and store back.
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 0, scrypt_add32(w0, o0))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 4, scrypt_add32(w1, o1))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 8, scrypt_add32(w2, o2))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 12, scrypt_add32(w3, o3))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 16, scrypt_add32(w4, o4))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 20, scrypt_add32(w5, o5))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 24, scrypt_add32(w6, o6))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 28, scrypt_add32(w7, o7))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 32, scrypt_add32(w8, o8))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 36, scrypt_add32(w9, o9))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 40, scrypt_add32(w10, o10))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 44, scrypt_add32(w11, o11))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 48, scrypt_add32(w12, o12))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 52, scrypt_add32(w13, o13))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 56, scrypt_add32(w14, o14))
    scrypt_store_le32(block_64, 60, scrypt_add32(w15, o15))

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 11: 32-bit ARX helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Salsa20 operates on 32-bit unsigned integers with addition, XOR, and
left-rotate modulo 2^32. These helpers implement those ops on Runa's
native 64-bit Integer, masking with 0xFFFFFFFF on each output.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
mask_u32 = 4294967295.
add32 : (a + b) AND 0xFFFFFFFF
xor32 : bitwise xor of two 32-bit values via byte-by-byte XOR
rotl32: ((x SHL n) OR (x SHR (32-n))) AND 0xFFFFFFFF
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) each. Inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Public ARX operations; no secret-dependent timing.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_add32" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let r be a plus b
    Return r modulo by 4294967296
End Process

@Reasoning
32-bit XOR using the native bitwise_xor operator. The result is masked
to 32 bits so callers operating on 32-bit Salsa20 words observe wraparound
semantics identical to a hardware XOR.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Single native bitwise_xor followed by a mask to 32 bits.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). One bitwise operation per call. At scrypt N=2^15 this replaces the
previous 32-iteration decomposition with a single instruction in the
emitted code, reducing the inner-loop cost by more than an order of
magnitude.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Constant-time on inputs: a single bitwise operation has no operand-
dependent branches.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_xor32" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let xored be a bitwise_xor b
    Return xored modulo by 4294967296
End Process

@Reasoning
32-bit left rotate by n bits.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
((x * 2^n) MOD 2^32) OR (x DIV 2^(32-n)) implemented arithmetically.
The OR is implemented by addition because the bit ranges don't overlap.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Public rotate amount.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_rotl32" takes x as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lo_part be x multiplied by scrypt_pow2(n)
    Set lo_part to lo_part modulo by 4294967296
    Let hi_part be x divided by scrypt_pow2(32 minus n)
    Return lo_part plus hi_part
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns 2^n for n in 0..32.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Iterative doubling.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(n) but n <= 32.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Public.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_pow2" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    Let r be 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n:
        Set r to r multiplied by 2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return r
End Process

@Reasoning
Load a 4-byte little-endian unsigned 32-bit integer from buf at offset.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Compose four byte loads with byte-significance weights.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Loading public input bytes.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_load_le32" takes buf as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Let b0 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buf, offset)
    Let b1 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buf, offset plus 1)
    Let b2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buf, offset plus 2)
    Let b3 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buf, offset plus 3)
    Return b0 plus (b1 multiplied by 256) plus (b2 multiplied by 65536) plus (b3 multiplied by 16777216)
End Process

@Reasoning
Store a 32-bit value as little-endian into buf at offset.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Four byte stores at offset, offset+1, offset+2, offset+3.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Public output bytes.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scrypt_store_le32" takes buf as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, offset, value modulo by 256)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, offset plus 1, (value divided by 256) modulo by 256)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, offset plus 2, (value divided by 65536) modulo by 256)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, offset plus 3, (value divided by 16777216) modulo by 256)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 12: KDF_derive - tag-driven dispatcher
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Unified entrypoint that dispatches on the algorithm tag. The params
buffer encodes algorithm-specific arguments as a length-prefixed
key/value blob.

For HKDF (any hash variant): params = salt_len(4 BE) salt info_len(4 BE)
  info hash_alg(4 BE) output_len(4 BE).
For Argon2id: t_cost(4) m_cost_kb(4) parallelism(4) output_len(4) salt_len(4) salt password_len(4) password.
For PBKDF2: iterations(4) hash_alg(4) output_len(4) salt_len(4) salt password_len(4) password.
For scrypt: N(4) r(4) p(4) output_len(4) salt_len(4) salt password_len(4) password.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Inspect the algorithm tag and decode params into the dedicated proc
arguments. Returns 1 on success after writing to the output buffer
specified at the end of the params blob.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Adds one decode pass to the underlying KDF.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The params blob may carry password / IKM; the caller is responsible for
zeroizing those after KDF_derive returns.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "KDF_derive" takes arena as Integer, algorithm as Integer, params as Integer, params_length as Integer, output as Integer returns Integer:
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If params is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If params_length is less than 16:
        Return 0
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_HKDF_SHA256:
        Return KDF_derive_hkdf(arena, Alg.ALG_SHA2_256, params, params_length, output)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_HKDF_SHA384:
        Return KDF_derive_hkdf(arena, Alg.ALG_SHA2_384, params, params_length, output)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_HKDF_SHA512:
        Return KDF_derive_hkdf(arena, Alg.ALG_SHA2_512, params, params_length, output)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ARGON2ID:
        Return KDF_derive_argon2id(arena, params, params_length, output)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_PBKDF2_HMAC_SHA256:
        Return KDF_derive_pbkdf2(arena, Alg.ALG_SHA2_256, params, params_length, output)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_PBKDF2_HMAC_SHA512:
        Return KDF_derive_pbkdf2(arena, Alg.ALG_SHA2_512, params, params_length, output)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SCRYPT:
        Return KDF_derive_scrypt(arena, params, params_length, output)
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Decode params blob for HKDF: 4 BE salt_len, salt_len bytes salt,
4 BE info_len, info_len bytes info, 4 BE output_len, 4 BE ikm_len,
ikm_len bytes ikm.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walk the buffer with bounds checking, then call hkdf_extract_then_expand.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(params_length).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
ikm is secret; reside in arena only as long as needed.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "KDF_derive_hkdf" takes arena as Integer, hash_alg as Integer, params as Integer, params_length as Integer, output as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be 0
    Let salt_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    If off plus salt_len is greater than params_length:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let salt_ptr be params plus off
    Set off to off plus salt_len
    Let info_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    If off plus info_len is greater than params_length:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let info_ptr be params plus off
    Set off to off plus info_len
    Let output_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let ikm_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    If off plus ikm_len is greater than params_length:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ikm_ptr be params plus off
    Return hkdf_extract_then_expand(arena, salt_ptr, salt_len, ikm_ptr, ikm_len, info_ptr, info_len, output_len, hash_alg, output)
End Process

@Reasoning
Decode Argon2id params: t(4) m(4) p(4) out(4) saltL(4) salt[] pwL(4) pw[].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Linear decode then argon2id_derive.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(params_length).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Password is secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "KDF_derive_argon2id" takes arena as Integer, params as Integer, params_length as Integer, output as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be 0
    Let t_cost be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let m_cost be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let parallelism be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let output_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let salt_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    If off plus salt_len is greater than params_length:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let salt_ptr be params plus off
    Set off to off plus salt_len
    Let pw_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    If off plus pw_len is greater than params_length:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pw_ptr be params plus off
    Return argon2id_derive(arena, pw_ptr, pw_len, salt_ptr, salt_len, t_cost, m_cost, parallelism, output_len, output)
End Process

@Reasoning
Decode PBKDF2 params: iter(4) hash(4) out(4) saltL(4) salt[] pwL(4) pw[].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Linear decode then pbkdf2_hmac.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(params_length).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Password is secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "KDF_derive_pbkdf2" takes arena as Integer, hash_alg as Integer, params as Integer, params_length as Integer, output as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be 0
    Let iterations be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let inner_hash be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let output_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let salt_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    If off plus salt_len is greater than params_length:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let salt_ptr be params plus off
    Set off to off plus salt_len
    Let pw_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    If off plus pw_len is greater than params_length:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pw_ptr be params plus off
    Let chosen_hash be hash_alg
    If inner_hash is not equal to 0:
        Set chosen_hash to inner_hash
    End If
    Return pbkdf2_hmac(arena, pw_ptr, pw_len, salt_ptr, salt_len, iterations, output_len, chosen_hash, output)
End Process

@Reasoning
Decode scrypt params: N(4) r(4) p(4) out(4) saltL(4) salt[] pwL(4) pw[].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Linear decode then scrypt.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(params_length).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Password is secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "KDF_derive_scrypt" takes arena as Integer, params as Integer, params_length as Integer, output as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be 0
    Let n_cost be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let r be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let p be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let output_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    Let salt_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    If off plus salt_len is greater than params_length:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let salt_ptr be params plus off
    Set off to off plus salt_len
    Let pw_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(params, off)
    Set off to off plus 4
    If off plus pw_len is greater than params_length:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pw_ptr be params plus off
    Return scrypt(arena, pw_ptr, pw_len, salt_ptr, salt_len, n_cost, r, p, output_len, output)
End Process
